<subSubSection id="748C08FAFF8B500137F892BA015691CC" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="3C295B71FF8B500137F892BA015691CC" blockId="5.[151,1437,1759,2038]" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8B500137F892BA026E90C0" bold="true" box="[199,315,1759,1785]" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was established by 
<bibRefCitation id="58072680FF8B500135929285003B90C0" author="Huo, K. - K. &amp; Ren, G. - D. &amp; Zheng, Z. - M." box="[685,878,1759,1786]" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" refId="ref5965" refString="Huo, K. - K., Ren, G. - D. &amp; Zheng, Z. - M. (2007) Fauna of Syrphidae from Mt. Qinling-Bashan in China (Insecta: Diptera). Chinese Agricultural Science and Technology Press, Beijing, 512 pp." type="book" year="2007">
Huo 
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8B500135DB9285004390C0" box="[740,790,1759,1785]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">et al</emphasis>
. (2007)
</bibRefCitation>
and originally placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="FB9620F2FF8B500133C792BA063090C0" authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1803" box="[1272,1381,1759,1785]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Microdon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8B500133C792BA063090C0" box="[1272,1381,1759,1785]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Microdon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="58072680FF8B5001324B928502CD9124" author="Reemer, M. &amp; Stahls, G." pageId="5" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 213" refId="ref6348" refString="Reemer, M. &amp; Stahls, G. (2013 a) Generic revision and species classification of the Microdontinae (Diptera: Syrphidae). ZooKeys, 288, 1 - 213." type="journal article" year="2013">Reemer &amp; Ståhls (2013a)</bibRefCitation>
transferred some species, including 
<taxonomicName id="FB9620F2FF8B500134099361075A9124" baseAuthorityName="Huo, Ren et Zheng" baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[822,1039,1795,1821]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Metadon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spuribifasciatus">
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8B500134099361075A9124" box="[822,1039,1795,1821]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">M. spuribifasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from genus 
<taxonomicName id="FB9620F2FF8B50013399936606469124" authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1803" box="[1190,1299,1795,1821]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Microdon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8B50013399936606469124" box="[1190,1299,1795,1821]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Microdon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="FB9620F2FF8B50013206936606C89124" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" box="[1337,1437,1795,1821]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Metadon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8B50013206936606C89124" box="[1337,1437,1795,1821]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Metadon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on characters of the mesopleuron and male genitalia. We found the external characters of this species were in accordance with those of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="FB9620F2FF8B50013579932E01FF915C" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" box="[582,682,1867,1893]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Metadon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8B50013579932E01FF915C" box="[582,682,1867,1893]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Metadon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including the katepimeron with wrinkled texture, katatergum with oblique rows of microtrichia, elongated abdomen, and the anepisternum pilose except for its ventral half. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="58072680FF8B500137DD93F101539194" author="Reemer, M. &amp; Stahls, G." box="[226,518,1938,1966]" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 213" refId="ref6348" refString="Reemer, M. &amp; Stahls, G. (2013 a) Generic revision and species classification of the Microdontinae (Diptera: Syrphidae). ZooKeys, 288, 1 - 213." type="journal article" year="2013">Reemer &amp; Ståhls (2013a)</bibRefCitation>
, in 
<taxonomicName id="FB9620F2FF8B5001350E93F601C09194" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" box="[561,661,1939,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Metadon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8B5001350E93F601C09194" box="[561,661,1939,1965]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Metadon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the anepisternum is usually entirely pilose or with a small bare part ventrally, except in 
<taxonomicName id="FB9620F2FF8B5001364E93DD01C291EB" authority="Matsumura" authorityName="Matsumura" box="[369,663,1975,2002]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Metadon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifasciatus">
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8B5001364E93DD015A91E8" box="[369,527,1975,2001]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">M. bifasciatus</emphasis>
Matsumura
</taxonomicName>
, the sibling species of 
<taxonomicName id="FB9620F2FF8B500134AD93DD073C91E8" baseAuthorityName="Huo, Ren et Zheng" baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[914,1129,1975,2001]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Metadon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spuribifasciatus">
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8B500134AD93DD073C91E8" box="[914,1129,1975,2001]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">M. spuribifasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in which the anepisternum is bare on the entire ventral half.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
